data.message: I'm kind of ambivalent about this. On the one hand those skills are obviously the ones that are going to be the most immediately useful, but it seems like they're also the kinds of things you can teach yourself if you're motivated, or that just require lots of practice. I think a big part of what makes the *degree* valuable long-term (as opposed to, say, experience or something like codeacademy) is the "science" part of computer science. I don't think it's a bad idea necessarily, but that would be my main concern

Immediately we can see two schools of thought regarding education between Gabe Pez-Coh and Moritz Gellner. On one hand we have education for the sake of education and enrichment, and on the other hand we have education for the sake of job preparation. In my opinion, there should be better "track" options, for going into what "Computer Science" is all about, or going into "Software Engineering" where the industry is hiring. 

As for now, this is why internships are valuable and you should start looking early.

I doubt the CS faculty will be amenable to this. It's been made clear by the faculty in the past that the CS program is not a "trade school", and that people who want to learn the industry should do so outside of school.

No harm in talking to Robby, though.

I think Lee Fan hit the nail right on the head. I don't think the the Northwestern curriculum should shift towards being more software development focus, because I agree with Moritz Gellner that it is an important part of the degree, I just think they should offer options for people who want to focus in software development since it's such a big part of computer science. Josiah Matlack I think that opinion might be changing, more and more people are entering CS and classes like NUvention are filling up so quickly that they are starting to notice the interest of the students, so I'm hoping Prof Findler will be open to the idea.

Hey guys, I'm pretty disappointed with the lack of a Software Development depth, so I was planning on talking to Professor Findler about it. I just wanted to see how many people felt the same way as I do, so I'd appreciate if it you would answer the question above. I was thinking that a software development depth would teach about different development techniques (agile,TDD, etc), would teach how to properly write test cases and unit tests, and, most importantly, allow us to create projects that are relevant, interesting to us, and will help prepare us for a software development career. Thanks for your time!

data.message:
Chief Technology Officer

Job description

Mission: We’re on a mission to connect ambitious high school students to opportunities they are genuinely passionate about. We don’t want students to participate in activities just to build an “impressive” resume. We want students to be admitted to the school of their dreams because they choose to do things in high school that are meaningful to them. Every student can find opportunities on Admit Hero and take initiative towards their college aspirations — we want to empower students to be their own heroes.

Product: We’re building a platform where students make an account, pick their interests & get a personalized feed of content, scholarships, student profiles, advice, and summer programs. [Currently we have a website up where viewers can access content but not make accounts, etc.] We differentiate our platform based on two factors: Content + Delivery.

-Content: Our content features students who have won scholarships, been accepted into colleges and opportunities, and are alumni of programs. We pair these profiles of real students with detailed guides and insightful advice on how to achieve similar feats as these students. Unlike anonymous internet forums, our content is verified and presented in a modern, design-first way.

-Delivery: Our delivery is a dynamic and filterable feed customized based on student interests. Since this feed is tailored for each student, we are not only producing high quality content (like a blog or magazine), but also allowing the user to own the experience of consuming content relevant to him or her. Since our feed aggregates opportunities of all sorts, including lots of our own content, we go way beyond being a traditional scholarship or internship search engine.

We will share information on Monetization and Competition with qualified potential candidates.

Product Roadmap: 1) MVP: We have set up a website to release content and are building a following and email subscriber list. 2) Content: We are in the process of recruiting for our content internship to generate high quality content. 3) Web App: We are in the process of developing our web app, which we hope to roll out in Spring 2016.

Founders: Our two founders are Northwestern seniors with relevant previous work experience. Our CEO/Product Manager is a business student with experience in finance through internships at Goldman Sachs and Discover Financial Services. In the past, he has founded a non-profit in high school with almost $40,000 in impact, along with winning over $90,000 worth of scholarships. Our COO/Product Marketer is a journalism student with extensive marketing experience (JellyVision, Asta Publications, Urban Bound, SavvyRoo, etc.) and has been profiled by Inbound.org as a leading marketer under the age of 22.

Requirements

Candidate Qualifications:
-Should have extensive previous experience programming who are looking to join a hardworking, mission-driven team
-Preferably experience in both backend and front end coding 
-Well-versed in Ruby on Rails, Javascript... [etc] but open to other languages too
-No age or degree requirement

This position is an equity position for CTO.

WANT TO LEARN MORE? SHOOT US AN EMAIL AT TEAM@ADMITHERO.COM!

Want to help develop a website, run a database, or build an app? How about joining and making a lasting impact on one of the largest student-run philanthropies in the nation to help raise money to end childhood hunger and support various programs in the Chicago area? Then you should apply for the Northwestern University Dance Marathon Technology and Analytics Committee! In addition to maintaining our website, nudm.org, we’ll be building up an internal portal and developing and analyzing our brand new database to make NUDM more efficient than ever. We're especially looking for people with experience in HTML, (S)CSS, PHP, and SQL, but there will be lots of opportunities for different skill levels, so as long as you're interested in learning, you don't need to know any of those.

There are also 9 other amazing committees that you can learn more about at nudm.org/committees/ . If you love NUDM or want to try it for the first time, there’s no better way to do it than being on a committee. It’s a great way to give back, make new friends, develop your skills and learn new ones, and working towards those last 30 hours all year makes them so much more special. 

To learn more, come to the NUDM 2016 Committee Info Session on Tuesday at 7 in Leverone Auditorium in the Kellogg building. Applications will be open until Saturday, October 3rd, at 11:59PM. Check out nudm.org/committees/ for more info, and feel free to reach out to me with any questions or concerns at tech@nudm.org.

We're looking for expertise in mobile (iOS (Swift) and Android) and backend (Python) development. You'll be working hands-on with a team of experienced hardware, UI/UX, mobile and backend developers.

AMPY makes a battery that charges as you move and a smartphone app that tracks your usage habits, predicts when your phone will run out of power, and helps you manage your battery life. We're shipping product now and working with several companies on integrating our hardware and software into wearables so you never have to plug them into the wall.
